<br>
I also forgot about DirectShow which is another of the major new updates to DirectX. Basically DirectShow is used to provide an API for streaming media (realtime play of video and audio over networks) in a variety of formats and is closely tied to Direct3D and DirectSound.<br>
<br>
I wouldn't agree however, that the other functionality is so old, and not worth talking about. The assumption that the computer industry could ever be &quot;old&quot; is absurd. Being a part of the industry myself I see these new technologies each and everyday in the various trade publications I receive.<br>
<br>
The industry is always moving in all aspects not just graphics and sound. There are new technologies being designed and implemented in keyboards, mice, joysticks, gamepads and network devices (e.g. cordless, optical, digital, analog and various data transfer methods) and as such DirectX needs to provide API's for these new technologies. <br>
<br>
Although graphics and sound are the major points of game development if you were limited to the input devices you could use and didn't have multiplayer functionality then the game would loose out to one that did. Sometimes even the smallest little functions add to the success of a game, so saying that these aren't important (obviously not as important but still important) is wrong.<br>
<br>
DirectX only limitation is it is made by Microsoft and as such isn't platform independent, however I believe it is one of the most wide ranged libraries available for games development. Most if not all of the competitors in this market provide platform independent solutions. For example:<br>
<br>
SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer)<br>
OpenGL (Graphics Libraries)<br>
OpenAL (Audio Libraries)<br>
Glide<br>
PLIB (portable game libraries)<br>
GGI (general graphics interface)<br>
<br>
and many more. However, these don't provide quite as much functionality as DirectX does and sometimes more than one library is required to gain complete functionality, which can someties lead to bugs and sluggish code. <br>
<br>
Of course not all games companies use precoded libraries. A few (of the stubborn ones) prefer to code their own graphics, sound, i/o and network engines and keep this code under tight wraps (for obvious commercial reasons e.g. licensing) until someone offers them enough money.<br>
<br>
I would say DirectX was more for multimedia, connectivity and I/O and as such is brilliant for games, but not limited just to that branch of development.<br>
<br>
Cheers<br>
<br>
